  • lots of interest in my poster from people working in other types of membrane trafficking besides CME, but didn't get any directly useful feedback
  • interesting in vitro systems being developed in Stachowiak lab to systematically add more CME proteins to EPS15 condensates and observe how they partition

Endocytic condensate theory project

recent progress

  • working on making flexible membrane model simulations more computationally efficient so we can validate toy model results with very long simulations
  • Vinu's modeling effort will be an important contribution to the overall story

next steps

  • hand off Vinu's results so I or we can integrate it into a variable area/curvature model; that might be the overarching framework for the manuscript
  • continue tweak simulation code to make it run more quickly and for more time steps
  • devise strategy for characterizing free energy landscape of my new flexible membrane model in analogous way to my original model

Endocytic condensate experimental project

purified protein approach

  • I think Nikhil could use a bit of a push getting constructs expressed, so I will take up just getting the published EPS15 and Fcho1 purified while he continues working on expressing/purifying the GFP fusions

in vivo approach

  • as Vinu touched on in lab meeting, I will try applying published FRAP guidelines to estimate diffusion coefficent and then surface tension from Ede1 FRAP data in order to constrain model
  • will try Yidi's Ede1 overexpression strain to see if that is easier to analyze
  • will also return to Ark/Prk mutant to see if that is amenable to drolpet merging and FRAP analysis as well

Mechanical role of Type I myosin in CME theory project

recent progress

  • soliciting comments from Matt and Ross on what is missing from the current story

next steps

my ideas I've had on low priority for a while:

short-term

  • subtract myo internalization measurements from -myo negative control to get effect of myo alone

  • plot number of myosin vs. internalization metric (similar to Mensnschijn et al. 2019)

  • look into myosin step size (currently avg. 5 nm)

long-term

  • collaborating with Matt and Padmini to draft the story as I work on it in this google doc
  • investigate how myosin may provide robustness, for instance in adaptation to higher membrane tension
  • develop metrics for measuring actin organization - Padmini suggested papers by Anders Carlsson
  • come up with outputs that can be experimentally tested
